Service Cloud Messaging combines messaging channels like WhatsApp, Facebook Messenger, Apple Messages for Business, SMS, and Bring Your Own Channel to provide a smooth conversation experience.

Seventy-five percent of adults want to communicate with brands through messaging. You can choose which channels to use to communicate with your customers, for example, setting up only a WhatsApp channel.

When customers need help from your business, they can message you on any channel youâ€™ve set up and get help from an agent or bot. Agents in most Messaging channels can also proactively start conversations with customers, or your company can set up automation to send notification messages to customers.

Routing by Omni-Channel assigns incoming messages to queues, bots, or agents using queue-based routing or Flow Builder for more complex scenarios.

Einstein Bots can be created for your Messaging channels to gather information from customers and resolve inquiries. A bot can be associated with multiple channels and complete tasks like greeting customers, gathering the reason for their message, or routing messages based on the customer's preferred language.

The Service Console shows incoming messages in the Omni-Channel utility or sidebar, just like phone calls. Agents can accept a message and start chatting.

Service Cloud Messaging limits and considerations should be reviewed before getting started with certain channels. Supported editions include messaging for In-App and Web, WhatsApp, Facebook Messenger, SMS, Apple Messages for Business, and Bring Your Own Channel.

New features are available exclusively in enhanced channels, Messaging for In-App and Web, and Bring Your Own Channel.
title: Service Cloud Messaging
